RbNO$_{3}$ takes on four distinct phases with increasing temperature (Shamsuzzoha, 1988): \begin{itemize} \item \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_hP45_144_3a_9a_3a-001}{Phase IV is the ground state}, stable up to 437K. \item Phase III, stable in the range 437-492K, is in \href{current_web_home_dir/A8B24C_cP33_207_g_k_a-001}{this disordered cubic structure}, where the NO$_{3}$ ions are centered on the halide site in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_cP2_221_a_b-002}{cesium chloride ($B2)$ structure}. \item Phase II, stable up to 564K, is possibly a body-centered cubic structure with up to eight formula units in the conventional unit cell. \item Phase I, stable up to the melting point, is thought to be a \href{current_web_home_dir/AB_cF8_225_a_b-001}{sodium chloride ($B1$) structure}, with NO$_{3}$ again playing the role of chlorine. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 The nitrogen and oxygen sites are filled 12.5\% of the time, so that only one nitrogen and three oxygens appear on any given halide site. 
 Prior to 2023 this was the only ICSD entry for \href{current_web_home_dir/cubic_spacegroup.html#sg207}{space group $P432$ \#207}.
